    3.8104813317580833`*^9}, {3.81048146789211*^9, 3.8104815557630205`*^9}, {
    3.8104817202872114`*^9, 3.8104817438715935`*^9}, 3.810481790764664*^9, 
    3.810481836241686*^9, {3.810481926951917*^9, 3.810481935802024*^9}, {
    3.8104820720505495`*^9, 3.8104821860076323`*^9}, {3.810482900850647*^9, 
    3.8104829123165646`*^9}, {3.8104829752587*^9, 3.8104829860744143`*^9}, {
    3.810483024639452*^9, 3.810483038492651*^9}, {3.8104830702023983`*^9, 
    3.8104830866522465`*^9}, {3.8104831187257876`*^9, 3.810483135292489*^9}, {
    3.8104831732744513`*^9, 3.8104831809128747`*^9}, {3.810646494275571*^9, 
    3.8106466133679247`*^9}, {3.810648134660228*^9, 3.81064819494398*^9}, 
    3.810648227529907*^9, {3.8106497988538876`*^9, 3.810649957534833*^9}, {
    3.81065029914425*^9, 3.8106503559481907`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->
  "96bd19af-1411-4377-aad1-0dcf1aba260c"],
 " is a normalization constant.  Note that the bounds on the left-hand side \
go from \[Minus]1 to 1 because \[Chi] = cos\[Theta], and these are thus \
equivalent to 0 to \[Pi] in \[Theta] space. Also note that the extra sin\
\[Theta] in the central integral arises from the volume element in spherical \
coordinates,"
}], "Text",
